While Ri reiterated familiar North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a phased approach to nuclear power that would reward North Korea as it took gradual steps, his statement seemed significant, as it did not reject a unilateral nuclear solution entirely as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work towards the “denuclearisation of the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first dismantle its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also rejected negotiations to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘decommissioning first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its purpose through coercion, even objecting to the ‘declaration to end the war’,” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can get us on our knees is a pipe dream for those people who lack knowledge about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions deepen our mistrust."
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that US leaders highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
The minister instead pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding, “If the party on this issue of nuclear disarmament were South Korea and not the United States, the Korean Peninsula’s nuclear disarmament would not have come to such a standstill.”
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was dramatically different than last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea’s future ability to reach the U.S. mainland with rockets was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “rocketman” on a suicide mission.
This year in the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking steps to disarm, but it said that much work still remains to be done and that sanctions must remain until North Korea disarms.
