Harvard Students Take Course on Getting Enough Rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has prompted all graduate students to improve their sleep habits in an effort to combat the growing macho culture of studying through caffeinated “durations.”
An academic study found that students at the world’s leading universities are often clueless about the very basics of how to care for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of it, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why don’t I get to know this until now, in my senior year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep – which surprised me.
The course, organized for the first time this year, explains to students the importance of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s Health Services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course includes a series of interactive assignments.
Part of the course includes a picture of a dorm room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of good sleep habits.
In another part, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know it won’t change students’ behavior right away.
But we think they have a right to know — just as you have a right to know about the health benefits of choosing to smoke cigarettes,” Professor Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in being “divine” still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Ensuring you have enough, good-quality sleep should be the student’s “secret weapon” to fight stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said — even to avoid weight gain because insomnia puts the brain into a state of starvation and makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course and has attended one of his courses last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said the course was an eye-opener and inspired him to campaign for a campus-wide course.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all doctoral students to complete a similar program of study before commencing their studies at the high-performing department.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when to go to bed and when to wake up and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic displays and LED lighting, which can cause you to turn around the clock, leading to sleep problems.
