Review of Johnny English Strikes Again - Powerless Spy Parody by Rowan Atkinson
It’s now tradition to look for Brexit meanings in every new film with a British tilt, and the same seems to apply to this remake of the latest Johnny English action comedy – a series of spy parodies that kicked off in 2003 with Johnny English and re-emerged in 2011 with Johnny English Reborn.
Will sharp satire about how obviously bad we are become the nation’s new export commodity?
In any case, the incompetent Johnny English with the rubber face got his license to blunder to sake renewed for the second time - his name signals more than anything else that he is a broad comic creation intended for cinema audiences even in non-English-speaking countries
He is, of course, the quirky secret agent, who despite his bizarre claims to smoothie glamour has gotten a little bit of Clouseau, a hint of Mr Bean and a measure of the guy from the opening ceremony of the London 2012 Olympics.
He is also originally based on the traveler and international mystery man that Atkinson once played in the now-forgotten Barclaycard TV ads that wreak havoc wherever he goes.
There are one or two great moments in the latest JE movie
I loved when Johnny English approaches a helicopter dressed in a medieval armor and when the rotor blades briefly hit his helmet.
Atkinson’s talent for physical comedy appears, but the humor feels rather low-key and strangely superfluous, especially since the “serious” movie brands like 007 and Mission Impossible themselves now offer comedy as an ingredient.
The humor feels like it is adapted for children instead of adults and for me, Johnny English's weird antics are not as inventive and focused as Atkinson's silent film exploits in the role of Bean.
The ever-present issue now is that Britain is in serious trouble.
A cyber-hacker has infiltrated Britain’s super-secret web network of spies, revealing the identities of all of Britain’s agents out in the field to the agent of the service’s great dissatisfaction – an extremely small role for Kevin Eldon.
It will be the last straw for a prime minister who is a pompous and hard-hitting figure, who is already suffering from a complete collapse of his political popularity: Emma Thompson is doing her very best with this quasi-Teresa-May character but the script offers little to work with.
Her intelligence adviser informs her that when every single active spy is busy, she must use someone who has retired.
And that means the stuttering Johnny English in person, now employed as a teacher in some affluent institution, but offering unofficial lessons in the art of working undercover on the side.
English was sent back to Whitehall for an emergency meeting and reunited with his former long-lived sidekick Bough, once again played by Ben Miller.
Bough is now married to a submarine captain, a jolly-hockey-sticks-role in which Vicki Pepperdine is near-wasted.
So Batman and Robin are back after everything went so terribly wrong on Her Majesty's Secret Service and encounter Olga Kurylenko's beautiful femme fatale Ophelia Bulletova.
Meanwhile, the Prime Minister will fall hard for the charismatic tech billionaire, who claims he can solve Britain’s computer troubles: the hapless Jason Volta, played by Jake Lacy.
English and Bough begin their odyssey of farcical antics: dressed as waiters, they set fire to a flashy French restaurant; they wreak havoc as they smuggle themselves aboard Volta’s luxury yacht; and English unleashes sheer anarchy as he tries to use a VR headset to familiarize himself with the inside of Volta’s house.
There is certainly a lot of work behind the latter sequence, but even though the film is both charming and fast-paced, it has an air of children's TV around it.
Pretty moderate all in all.
And as with the other Johnny English films, I can’t help but think: Can’t the British film industry give Rowan Atkinson a role that matches his talent?
