The study, conducted by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will follow southern and dwarf pipit trees as well as brown loaned and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Expert audio analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat sounds and which species do what.
A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed area map of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, conservation advisor for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to the bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain woodlands for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work affecting nests and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can airplanes and some chemical treatments of building materials as well as attacks from house cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to find insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, examine nests, and sometimes perform rescue operations.
The organisation has also established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at the Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten species of bat.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal area for them.
“Here at Threave, we have a good area for bats,” he said.
“We have the old buildings, lots of veteran trees and a variety of favorable habitats.
But there’s a lot about bats that’s still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties helps us understand more about what they need to thrive.
He stresses the importance of searching for bats before performing maintenance in real estate, as it is possible that the accidental destruction of a single nest could kill up to 400 females and young, and possibly wipe out an entire population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, disturb or disturb them or destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don’t know how their populations are doing.”
