Algal blooms: Decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission shows an overall decrease in concentrations of algal blooms for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Commission, more uneven blooms are reported in the areas around the larger municipalities of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which may indicate reduced levels.
The algal bloom extends along more than 200 kilometers of the coast, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee.
Spots can be seen about a mile out to sea outside Hillsborough, but in fewer places than last week.
Algal blooms have also been observed in the larger municipality of Pasco.
Medium concentrations on or off the coast of Pinellas have been reported over the past week: off the coast of Hillsborough low to high concentrations, background concentrations to high concentrations in Manatee, background concentrations to high concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota, background concentrations to medium concentrations on or off the coast of Lee, and low concentrations in Collier.
Reports of respiratory irritation continue to come from the municipalities of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There were no reports of respiratory irritation in northwest Florida last week.
